<doc id="32245" wikidata="Q1417809" url="?curid=32245" title="Universal property">
<text>In mathematics, more specifically in category theory, a universal property is a property that characterizes up to an isomorphism the result of some constructions. Thus, universal properties can be used for defining some objects independently from the method chosen for constructing them. For example, the definitions of the integers from the natural numbers, of the rational numbers from the integers, of the real numbers from the rational numbers, and of polynomial rings from the field of their coefficients can all be done in terms of universal properties. In particular, the concept of universal property allows a simple proof that all constructions of real numbers are equivalent: it suffices to prove that they satisfy the same universal property. 

Technically, a universal property is defined in terms of categories and functors by means of a universal morphism (see , below). Universal morphisms can also be thought more abstractly as initial or terminal objects of a comma category (see , below). 

Universal properties occur almost everywhere in mathematics, and the use of the concept allows the use of general properties of universal properties for easily proving some properties that would need boring verifications otherwise. For example, given a commutative ring , the field of fractions of the quotient ring of by a prime ideal can be identified with the residue field of the localization of at ; that is formula_1 (all these constructions can be defined by universal properties).

Other objects that can be defined by universal properties include: all free objects, direct products and direct sums, free groups, free lattices, Grothendieck group, completion of a metric space, completion of a ring, Dedekind–MacNeille completion, product topologies, Stone–Čech compactification, tensor products, inverse limit and direct limit, kernels and cokernels, quotient groups, quotient vector spaces, and other quotient spaces.

== Motivation ==

Before giving a formal definition of universal properties, we offer some motivation for studying such constructions.

* The concrete details of a given construction may be messy, but if the construction satisfies a universal property, one can forget all those details: all there is to know about the construction is already contained in the universal property. Proofs often become short and elegant if the universal property is used rather than the concrete details. For example, the tensor algebra of a vector space is slightly complicated to construct, but much easier to deal with by its universal property.
* Universal properties define objects uniquely up to a unique isomorphism. Therefore, one strategy to prove that two objects are isomorphic is to show that they satisfy the same universal property.
* Universal constructions are functorial in nature: if one can carry out the construction for every object in a category &quot;C&quot; then one obtains a functor on &quot;C&quot;. Furthermore, this functor is a right or left adjoint to the functor &quot;U&quot; used in the definition of the universal property.
* Universal properties occur everywhere in mathematics. By understanding their abstract properties, one obtains information about all these constructions and can avoid repeating the same analysis for each individual instance.

==Formal definition==
To understand the definition of a universal construction, it is important to look at examples. Universal constructions were not defined out of thin air, but were rather defined after mathematicians began noticing a pattern in many mathematical constructions (see Examples below). Hence, the definition may not make sense to one at first, but will become clear when one reconciles it with concrete examples.

Let formula_2 be a functor between categories formula_3 and formula_4. In what follows, let formula_5 be an object of formula_4, formula_7 and formula_8 be objects of formula_3, and formula_10 be a morphism in formula_3. 

Then, the functor formula_12 maps formula_7, formula_8 and formula_15 in formula_3 to formula_17, formula_18 and formula_19 in formula_4.

A universal morphism from formula_5 to formula_12 is a unique pair formula_23 in formula_4 which has the following property, commonly referred to as a universal property:

For any morphism of the form 
formula_25 in formula_4, there exists a &quot;unique&quot; morphism formula_10 in formula_3 such that the following diagram commutes:

We can dualize this categorical concept. A universal morphism from formula_12 to formula_5 is a unique pair formula_31 that satisfies the following universal property:

For any morphism of the form formula_32 in formula_4, there exists a &quot;unique&quot; morphism formula_34 in formula_3 such that the following diagram commutes:
Note that in each definition, the arrows are reversed. Both definitions are necessary to describe universal constructions which appear in mathematics; but they also arise due to the inherent duality present in category theory.
In either case, we say that the pair formula_36 which behaves as above satisfies a universal property.

==Connection with comma categories==
Universal morphisms can be described more concisely as initial and terminal objects in a comma category (i.e. one where morphisms are seen as objects in their own right).

Let formula_2 be a functor and formula_5 an object of formula_4. Then recall that the comma category formula_40 is the category where 
* Objects are pairs of the form formula_41, where formula_42 is an object in formula_3
* A morphism from formula_41 to formula_45 is given by a morphism formula_46 in formula_3 such that the diagram commutes:

Now suppose that the object formula_23 in formula_40 is initial. Then
for every object formula_50, there exists a unique morphism formula_10 such that the following diagram commutes. 
Note that the equality here simply means the diagrams are the same. Also note that the diagram on the right side of the equality is the exact same as the one offered in defining a universal morphism from formula_5 to formula_12. Therefore, we see that a universal morphism from formula_5 to formula_12 is equivalent to an initial object in the comma category formula_40.

Conversely, recall that the comma category formula_57 is the category where 
*Objects are pairs of the form formula_58 where formula_42 is an object in formula_3
*A morphism from formula_61 to formula_62 is given by a morphism formula_46 in formula_3 such that the diagram commutes:
Suppose formula_65 is a terminal object in formula_57. Then for every object formula_67, 
there exists a unique morphism formula_68 such that the following diagrams commute. 
The diagram on the right side of the equality is the same diagram pictured when defining a universal morphism from formula_12 to formula_5. Hence, a universal morphism from formula_12 to formula_5 corresponds with a terminal object in the comma category 
formula_57.

==Examples==

Below are a few examples, to highlight the general idea. The reader can construct numerous other examples by consulting the articles mentioned in the introduction.

===Tensor algebras===

Let formula_3 be the category of vector spaces formula_75-Vect over a field formula_75 and let formula_4 be the category of algebras formula_75-Alg over formula_75 (assumed to be unital and associative). Let
:formula_80 : formula_75-Alg → formula_75-Vect
be the forgetful functor which assigns to each algebra its underlying vector space.

Given any vector space formula_83 over formula_75 we can construct the tensor algebra formula_85. The tensor algebra is characterized by the fact:
:“Any linear map from formula_83 to an algebra formula_7 can be uniquely extended to an algebra homomorphism from formula_85 to formula_7.”
This statement is an initial property of the tensor algebra since it expresses the fact that the pair formula_90, where formula_91 is the inclusion map, is a universal morphism from the vector space formula_83 to the functor formula_80.

Since this construction works for any vector space formula_83, we conclude that formula_95 is a functor from formula_75-Vect to formula_75-Alg. This means that formula_95 is &quot;left adjoint&quot; to the forgetful functor formula_80 (see the section below on relation to adjoint functors).

===Products===

A categorical product can be characterized by a universal construction. For concreteness, one may consider the Cartesian product in Set, the direct product in Grp, or the product topology in Top, where products exist.

Let formula_5 and formula_101 be objects of a category formula_3 with finite products. The product of formula_5 and formula_101 is an object formula_5 × formula_101 together with two morphisms
:formula_107 : formula_108
:formula_109 : formula_110
such that for any other object formula_111 of formula_3 and morphisms formula_113 and formula_114 there exists a unique morphism formula_115 such that formula_116 and formula_117.

To understand this characterization as a universal property, take the category formula_4 to be the product category formula_119 and define the diagonal functor
: formula_120
by formula_121 and formula_122. Then formula_123 is a universal morphism from formula_124 to the object formula_125 of formula_119: if formula_127 is any morphism from formula_128 to formula_125, then it must equal
a morphism formula_130 from formula_131
to formula_132 followed by formula_133. As a commutative diagram:
For the example of the Cartesian product in Set, the morphism formula_133 comprises the two projections formula_135 and formula_136. Given any set formula_111 and functions formula_138 the unique map such that the required diagram commutes is given by formula_139.

===Limits and colimits===

Categorical products are a particular kind of limit in category theory. One can generalize the above example to arbitrary limits and colimits.

Let formula_140 and formula_3 be categories with formula_140 a small index category and let formula_143 be the corresponding functor category. The &quot;diagonal functor&quot;
:formula_144
is the functor that maps each object formula_145 in formula_3 to the constant functor formula_147 (i.e. formula_148 for each formula_5 in formula_140 and formula_151 for each formula_152 in formula_140) and each morphism formula_154 in formula_3 to the natural transformation formula_156 in formula_157 defined as, for every object formula_5 of formula_140, the component formula_160
at formula_5. In other words, the natural transformation is the one defined by having constant component formula_162 for every object of formula_140.

Given a functor formula_164 (thought of as an object in formula_143), the &quot;limit&quot; of formula_12, if it exists, is nothing but a universal morphism from formula_124 to formula_12. Dually, the &quot;colimit&quot; of formula_12 is a universal morphism from formula_12 to formula_124.

==Properties==

===Existence and uniqueness===

Defining a quantity does not guarantee its existence. Given a functor formula_2 and an object formula_5 of formula_4, 
there may or may not exist a universal morphism from formula_5 to formula_12. If, however, a universal morphism formula_36 does exist, then it is essentially unique. 
Specifically, it is unique up to a &quot;unique&quot; isomorphism: if formula_178 is another pair, then there exists a unique isomorphism 
formula_179 such that formula_180.
This is easily seen by substituting formula_181 in the definition of a universal morphism.

It is the pair formula_36 which is essentially unique in this fashion. The object formula_7 itself is only unique up to isomorphism. Indeed, if formula_36 is a universal morphism and formula_179 is any isomorphism then the pair formula_178, where formula_180 is also a universal morphism.

===Equivalent formulations===

The definition of a universal morphism can be rephrased in a variety of ways. Let formula_2 be a functor and let formula_5 be an object of formula_4. Then the following statements are equivalent:
* formula_36 is a universal morphism from formula_5 to formula_12
* formula_36 is an initial object of the comma category formula_40
* formula_196 is a representation of formula_197, where its components formula_198 are defined by

formula_199

for each object formula_42 in formula_201

The dual statements are also equivalent:
* formula_36 is a universal morphism from formula_12 to formula_5
* formula_36 is a terminal object of the comma category formula_57
* formula_207 is a representation of formula_208, where its components formula_209 are defined by

formula_210

for each object formula_42 in formula_201

===Relation to adjoint functors===

Suppose formula_213 is a universal morphism from formula_214 to formula_12 and formula_216 is a universal morphism from formula_217 to formula_12. 
By the universal property of universal morphisms, given any morphism formula_219 there exists a unique morphism formula_220 such that the following diagram commutes:
If &quot;every&quot; object formula_221 of formula_4 admits a universal morphism to formula_12, then the assignment formula_224 and formula_225 defines a functor formula_226. The maps formula_227 then define a natural transformation from formula_228 (the identity functor on formula_4) to formula_230. The functors formula_231 are then a pair of adjoint functors, with formula_232 left-adjoint to formula_12 and formula_12 right-adjoint to formula_232.

Similar statements apply to the dual situation of terminal morphisms from formula_12. If such morphisms exist for every formula_5 in formula_3 one obtains a functor formula_239 which is right-adjoint to formula_12 (so formula_12 is left-adjoint to formula_232).

Indeed, all pairs of adjoint functors arise from universal constructions in this manner. Let formula_12 and formula_232 be a pair of adjoint functors with unit formula_245 and co-unit formula_246 
(see the article on adjoint functors for the definitions). Then we have a universal morphism for each object in formula_3 and formula_4:
*For each object formula_5 in formula_3, formula_251 is a universal morphism from formula_5 to formula_232. That is, for all formula_254 there exists a unique formula_255 for which the following diagrams commute.
*For each object formula_101 in formula_4, formula_258 is a universal morphism from formula_12 to formula_101. That is, for all formula_255 there exists a unique formula_254 for which the following diagrams commute.

Universal constructions are more general than adjoint functor pairs: a universal construction is like an optimization problem; it gives rise to an adjoint pair if and only if this problem has a solution for every object of formula_3 (equivalently, every object of formula_4).

== History ==
Universal properties of various topological constructions were presented by Pierre Samuel in 1948. They were later used extensively by Bourbaki. The closely related concept of adjoint functors was introduced independently by Daniel Kan in 1958.

